Two options to deal with the UPSERT from @hannes from discord. Leaving it here as it might help other people. Both use an intermediate, staging table. 
Option 1
```
create table maintable (id integer, val string);
insert into maintable values (42, 'Hello'), (84, 'World');

create table staging (id integer, val string);
insert into staging values (42, 'Hello'), (1337, 'Quack');

insert into maintable select * From staging where id not in (select id from maintable);  
```

Option 2
```
create table maintable (id integer, val string);
insert into maintable values (42, 'Hello'), (84, 'World');

create table staging (id integer, val string);
insert into staging values (42, 'New Hello'), (1337, 'Quack');

select * from maintable;

delete from maintable where id in (select id from staging);

insert into maintable select * From staging where id not in (select id from maintable);

select * from maintable;
```

I'd like to add my 2 cents to this discussion because we use DuckDB in production and faced this issue.

@kuatroka It's not really clear to me what exactly Option 1 accomplishes as it doesn't update any values at all.  Inserting the non-existent values is fine but no updates are being executed here.

Option 2 is currently what we use.  This is effective in the sense that it is correct and fast, but the one big problem with this is the fact that DuckDB still does not vacuum deletes.  Meaning that if you run some procedure where you are upserting values daily, the footprint of the table on disk will grow according to the number of rows being inserted AND the number of rows being updated.  This is a bit annoying as your database file grows faster than it really should.  I'm not clear if this is true or not, but it could also make other queries you perform on that table slower than need be.  I think for this option to be really the best option, you will need to address this in some way.
